{"type":"message","id":"8293b7cf","parentId":"6e33cce1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:29:01.372Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see `gpu` and `Sandbox` in Modal's API. Let me think about how to approach this.\n\nLooking at Modal's capabilities:\n- `modal.Sandbox` - run code in a sandboxed environment\n- `modal.gpu` - GPU configuration\n- `modal.server` - might be a server running on Modal\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach for Modal with GPU inference is to use `modal.Sandbox` to run a lightweight inference server, or use `modal.Server` to serve something.\n\nActually wait - let me look at `modal.server` and `modal.gpu` more carefully. Maybe I should use `modal.Sandbox` to create a sandbox with GPU that runs Ollama, and then have the web app communicate with it.\n\n\nLet me reconsider the architecture: the web app runs in one container while the inference runs in a separate GPU-enabled sandbox, and they'd communicate internally through Modal's network. I should explore whether Modal already has built-in inference patterns or if I need to use their serve function to handle this properly.","thinkingSignature":"1b7fcb5627c0d1fe00ced850e82b6f8d7d7a5dfa3e39491d4e36ffb117cfbe7f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_gp3lvdm5kkyz_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"import modal; help(modal.gpu)\" 2>&1 | head -40","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":114439,"output":271,"cacheRead":13992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":128702,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774326533415}}
{"type":"message","id":"103d4e57","parentId":"8293b7cf","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:29:02.574Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_gp3lvdm5kkyz_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\Python\\Python314\\site-packages\\modal\\_utils\\async_utils.py:45: DeprecationWarning: 'asyncio.WindowsSelectorEventLoopPolicy' is deprecated and slated for removal in Python 3.16\r\n  asyncio.set_event_loop_policy(asyncio.WindowsSelectorEventLoopPolicy())\r\nC:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\Python\\Python314\\site-packages\\modal\\_utils\\async_utils.py:45: DeprecationWarning: 'asyncio.set_event_loop_policy' is deprecated and slated for removal in Python 3.16\r\n  asyncio.set_event_loop_policy(asyncio.WindowsSelectorEventLoopPolicy())\r\nHelp on module modal.gpu in modal:\r\n\r\nNAME\r\n    modal.gpu - **GPU configuration shortcodes**\r\n\r\nDESCRIPTION\r\n    You can pass a wide range of `str` values for the `gpu` parameter of\r\n    [`@app.function`](https://modal.com/docs/reference/modal.App#function).\r\n\r\n    For instance:\r\n    - `gpu=\"H100\"` will attach 1 H100 GPU to each container\r\n    - `gpu=\"L40S\"` will attach 1 L40S GPU to each container\r\n    - `gpu=\"T4:4\"` will attach 4 T4 GPUs to each container\r\n\r\n    You can see a list of Modal GPU options in the\r\n    [GPU docs](https://modal.com/docs/guide/gpu).\r\n\r\n    **Example**\r\n\r\n    ```python\r\n    @app.function(gpu=\"A100-80GB:4\")\r\n    def my_gpu_function():\r\n        ... # This will have 4 A100-80GB with each container\r\n    ```\r\n\r\n    **Deprecation notes**\r\n\r\n    An older deprecated way to configure GPU is also still supported,\r\n    but will be removed in future versions of Modal. Examples:\r\n\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.H100()` will attach 1 H100 GPU to each container\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.T4(count=4)` will attach 4 T4 GPUs to each container\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.A100()` will attach 1 A100-40GB GPUs to each container\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.A100(size=\"80GB\")` will attach 1 A100-80GB GPUs to each container\r\n\r\nCLASSES"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1157,"aggregated":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\Python\\Python314\\site-packages\\modal\\_utils\\async_utils.py:45: DeprecationWarning: 'asyncio.WindowsSelectorEventLoopPolicy' is deprecated and slated for removal in Python 3.16\r\n  asyncio.set_event_loop_policy(asyncio.WindowsSelectorEventLoopPolicy())\r\nC:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\Python\\Python314\\site-packages\\modal\\_utils\\async_utils.py:45: DeprecationWarning: 'asyncio.set_event_loop_policy' is deprecated and slated for removal in Python 3.16\r\n  asyncio.set_event_loop_policy(asyncio.WindowsSelectorEventLoopPolicy())\r\nHelp on module modal.gpu in modal:\r\n\r\nNAME\r\n    modal.gpu - **GPU configuration shortcodes**\r\n\r\nDESCRIPTION\r\n    You can pass a wide range of `str` values for the `gpu` parameter of\r\n    [`@app.function`](https://modal.com/docs/reference/modal.App#function).\r\n\r\n    For instance:\r\n    - `gpu=\"H100\"` will attach 1 H100 GPU to each container\r\n    - `gpu=\"L40S\"` will attach 1 L40S GPU to each container\r\n    - `gpu=\"T4:4\"` will attach 4 T4 GPUs to each container\r\n\r\n    You can see a list of Modal GPU options in the\r\n    [GPU docs](https://modal.com/docs/guide/gpu).\r\n\r\n    **Example**\r\n\r\n    ```python\r\n    @app.function(gpu=\"A100-80GB:4\")\r\n    def my_gpu_function():\r\n        ... # This will have 4 A100-80GB with each container\r\n    ```\r\n\r\n    **Deprecation notes**\r\n\r\n    An older deprecated way to configure GPU is also still supported,\r\n    but will be removed in future versions of Modal. Examples:\r\n\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.H100()` will attach 1 H100 GPU to each container\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.T4(count=4)` will attach 4 T4 GPUs to each container\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.A100()` will attach 1 A100-40GB GPUs to each container\r\n    - `gpu=modal.gpu.A100(size=\"80GB\")` will attach 1 A100-80GB GPUs to each container\r\n\r\nCLASSES","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774326542553}}
{"type":"message","id":"2517e456","parentId":"103d4e57","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:29:13.081Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see how Modal GPU works. I can add `gpu=\"A100\"` to the `@app.function()` decorator to get GPU access. This is the key insight I was missing.\n\nLet me rewrite the app to use `gpu=\"A100\"` on the function that needs GPU access. Since Ollama likely won't work, I should use a different approach for inference.\n\nLet me think about what's available on Modal:\n1. **llama-stack** - Modal might support it\n2. **vLLM** - popular inference server for open models\n3. **Direct model loading with transformers** - load Qwen with HuggingFace transformers + torch\n\nActually, the cleanest approach for Modal: use `modal.Sandbox` to create a GPU-enabled sandbox, run a Python script with vLLM or llama.cpp in it, and then communicate with it.\n\n\nBut the real constraint here is that Ollama's GPU detection fails in Modal's containerized environment even with the right GPU attached. Instead of fighting that, I should bypass Ollama entirely and load the model directly with HuggingFace's transformers library using PyTorch, which will properly utilize the A100. Though I'm realizing `transformers` and `torch` aren't pre-installed in the base Modal image, so I need to account for that dependency.\n\nLet me explore a few paths: I could install vLLM in the container to serve Qwen more efficiently, or try the transformers route with custom CUDA kernels. Actually, llama-stack might already be available on Modal since the image already has it installed. Let me check what's actually in that image and whether I can leverage llama-stack to avoid building inference from scratch.","thinkingSignature":"15c84c12026a7d2d63beee238b73d985cec68f5b3f5f8bb0c4eead31da5cd174"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5umk7dxuv0f2_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"import modal; help(modal.Sandbox)\" 2>&1 | head -60","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":115210,"output":394,"cacheRead":13992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":129596,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774326542577}}
