{"type":"message","id":"079b3bca","parentId":"87023b52","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:35:06.225Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still getting \"All connection attempts failed\". This is consistent - the `/health` GET endpoint is not working, but POST endpoints seem to work (they return JSON decode errors, which means they reached the server).Let me look at the health endpoint code again to see what could cause it to hang without even returning a response.\n\n```python\n@app.get(\"/health\")\nasync def health():\n    if _ollama_state[\"status\"] == \"unknown\":\n        import threading\n        t = threading.Thread(target=_start_ollama_bg, daemon=True)\n        t.start()\n\n    return {\n        \"status\": \"ok\",\n        \"ollama\": _ollama_state[\"status\"],\n        \"model\": MODEL_NAME,\n    }\n```\n\nOh! I see the problem now. When `_ollama_state[\"status\"]` is \"unknown\", we're spawning a daemon thread that calls `_start_ollama_bg`. That function tries to start Ollama using subprocess calls and waits for it to initialize, which could be blocking or hanging in a way that prevents the response from being sent back.\n\nThe real issue might be that the Modal container has the GPU available (we didn't get an error when deploying), but Ollama can't initialize the GPU or load the model properly. Or maybe `subprocess.Popen` is hanging indefinitely without timing out, causing the thread to never return and somehow blocking the async health check even though the thread should be independent.\n\nActually, I think I found it - the `subprocess.Popen` call with `stdout=subprocess.DEVNULL, stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL` might be the culprit.\n\nWait, no. The `/health` endpoint defines a GET handler, but the route is defined as `@api.get(\"/health\")`. Let me trace through what's actually happening when the request comes in.\n\nThe real problem might be that Modal is spinning up a new container with the GPU requirement, but it's taking longer to initialize than the request timeout, so the old container without GPU is still handling requests while the new one is still starting up.\n\nActually, I think the simplest explanation is that the daemon thread is blocking in `_start_ollama_bg`, which prevents the response from being sent. Let me try removing the threading call entirely and just return the health status immediately to test if that works.","thinkingSignature":"54aa640dc4b4acfdb66e94e659b2f3982042bee61d84116ec8dc77ddf7d80cc3"},{"type":"text","text":"The POST routes work (they return proper errors). The GET `/health` is hanging — the daemon thread is blocking in a way that blocks the response. Let me strip it down to bare metal:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_166tnymbhfts_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\spark\\modal_spark.py","oldText":"    @api.get(\"/health\")\n    async def health():\n        if _ollama_state[\"status\"] == \"unknown\":\n            import threading\n            t = threading.Thread(target=_start_ollama_bg, daemon=True)\n            t.start()\n\n        return {\n            \"status\": \"ok\",\n            \"ollama\": _ollama_state[\"status\"],\n            \"model\": MODEL_NAME,\n        }","newText":"    @api.get(\"/health\")\n    async def health():\n        return {\n            \"status\": \"ok\",\n            \"ollama\": _ollama_state[\"status\"],\n            \"model\": MODEL_NAME,\n        }"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":118255,"output":689,"cacheRead":13992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":132936,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774326887366}}
