{"type":"message","id":"aed87324","parentId":"4cbff5d1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:50:51.991Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now let me deploy and test. This should work because:\n1. The `OllamaService` class has `gpu=\"A100\"` so it gets a GPU\n2. The first time any method is called, `_ensure_ollama` starts Ollama and pulls the model\n3. The container stays warm for 600 seconds (scaledown_window), so Ollama keeps running\n4. Subsequent calls are fast because Ollama is already running\n\nBut wait - there's still a potential issue. When `health` is called, it calls `_ensure_ollama` which starts Ollama. But `health` is an `@modal.method()` - does it wait for `_ensure_ollama` to complete? \n \nLooking at the implementation, `_ensure_ollama` is just a regular Python method that gets called synchronously before the health check proceeds, so it blocks until Ollama is ready. That means a cold-start health check would wait for the server to start up and potentially pull the model, which could take time on the first call. Let me trace through the flow: `health.remote()` triggers `_ensure_ollama`, which starts Ollama and pulls the model if needed, then returns so the actual health check can run. `health.remote()` would wait for the full `_ensure_ollama` to complete, which could take several minutes on first call. For a health check that should return immediately, I should split this into two methods—one that just reports status without blocking, and another that handles the startup. But actually, the class-level `scaledown_window=600` means the container stays warm for 10 minutes after each request, so Ollama and the model persist between calls. I could use a module-level flag to track whether initialization has already happened, so subsequent health checks skip the setup entirely.\n\nFor now, let me just deploy and see what happens. If the first health check takes too long, we can iterate.","thinkingSignature":"24a012a547bb5548