{"type":"message","id":"55b8423c","parentId":"102b16f1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:52:30.521Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - the web function is calling `OllamaService.health.remote()` but it should be calling `OllamaService().health.remote()`. Let me fix the web server to instantiate the class.Actually wait - that's not right either. In Modal, you call class methods via `MyClass.method.remote()` (without instantiating). But the error says \"Did you forget to instantiate the class first?\" - so maybe Modal requires `MyClass().method.remote()` for some reason.\n\nActually, looking at Modal docs: to call a class method, you use `MyClass.method.remote()` where `MyClass` is the class itself (not an instance). \n\nThe error is confusing because I'm passing `OllamaService` directly to the web function in a different container than where `OllamaService` is defined, so it doesn't have the class available to call. I need to use Modal's `Cls` class properly to call methods on a GPU class from the web function, since the web function and the GPU class are running in different containers.\n\nLooking at how Modal's web server pattern works, when I define a web function in the same app as a `@modal.cls`, I should be able to call the class methods directly with `.remote()`. But I'm realizing the `gpu=\"A100\"` setting at the class level means all methods on that class get an A100 GPU, which might be affecting how the class is instantiated or how the method calls work.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that `OllamaService` needs to be imported or passed correctly in the web function context. The error about not being instantiated suggests Modal is treating it as a regular class rather than a Modal class. Let me try calling `OllamaService.health.remote()` instead of using the explicit `()` notation.","thinkingSignature":"c67df8ed4ad230ea0d085b33c226349b3bc352170d1c0e60bc2f52fc44cda27a"},{"type":"text","text":"\nThe error is abou