{"type":"message","id":"c0c0ce62","parentId":"d41ffe0a","timestamp":"2026-03-24T05:40:01.007Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm, those don't exist. Let me just try using the `nano-pdf` skill to extract the PDF content. Actually, I could also try using `subprocess` to call pdftoppm from poppler if it's installed, or use a different PDF to image conversion.\n\nActually, let me try a completely different approach. Let me check if there's a way to render the PDF pages using Windows built-in tools, or if there's a way to use the Telegram file path directly.\n\nWait - the media_inbound file is already 590KB which means it's the full PDF. Let me check if I can read the raw bytes and see if there's image data embedded.Let me try one more thing - using `pdf2image` with the poppler path specified explicitly. Or let me just try to use `pymupdf` from the workspace deps where I installed it earlier.Actually, I think the best approach is to just ask the user to describe the key findings from the PDF, or ask them to copy/paste the text. \n\nI'm going in circles with this PDF extraction. Let me pivot to what actually matters and work with the training logs Zach shared instead.","thinkingSignature":"35bde7822b1cc6c993e407539fd6485de04ba2eb33b53970ef96551840decda6"},{"type":"text","text":"Can't get the PDF conversion working — the image-based PDF needs OCR which needs tools I don't have set up. Let me just work with what you pasted.\n\n**Quick take on the SR-MoE logs from what you showed me:**\n\n`skip=0.79` is the death knell. That's not routing — that's the model learning to bypass the MoE layer entirely. Classic symptom of the routing auxiliary loss being too weak relative to the main task loss. The router finds out \"hey, if I just pass through the input unchanged, I still get reasonable loss, and I avoid the overhead of expert selection.\"\n\nWhat it means functionally: your model is acting like a thinner residual network, not a MoE. The 0.79 skip means 79% of tokens get zero expert activation.\n\n**Fixes to try:**\n\n1. **Cut the skip/identity path intentionally** — add a straight-through gradient term that forces SOMETHING through the experts, or use a learned gating that's biased away from the null route\n2. **Increase routing loss weight** — if your auxiliary load-balancing loss is too low, the router learns to be lazy\n3. **Smaller top-K** — if K=2 and skip is 0.79, that means even routing to 2 experts is being avoided; try K=1 with a confidence threshold instead\n4. **Check your router architecture** — if the router is a single linear layer with softmax, it might be collapsing to a near-zero vector for most tokens\n\nWhat's your routing auxiliary loss formulation? And what does your router embedding dimension look like relative to the model hidden dim?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":111895,"output":574,"cacheRead":13992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":126461,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774330779382}}
{"type":"message","id":"c74090a2","parentId":"c0c0ce62","timestamp":"2026-03-24T05:41:55.617Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-03-24 01:39:28 EDT] Exec completed (mild-ree, code 1) :: \\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\Python\\Python314\\site-packages\\pymupdf\\__init__.py\", line 33, in <module>[0m [31;1m from . import extra[0m [31;1m File \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming…\n\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"149\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 01:41 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nPhase 1: Supervised pre-training (2000 ep)\n ep 0: loss=5.7507 acc=0.000 route_ce=1.1545 div=0.0561 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 200: loss=3.5778 acc=0.900 route_ce=1.1257 div=0.0601 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 400: loss=2.5288 acc=0.850 route_ce=1.0730 div=0.0622 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 600: loss=2.4767 acc=0.800 route_ce=1.0678 div=0.0624 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 800: loss=2.6701 acc=0.750 route_ce=1.0638 div=0.0624 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 1000: loss=2.4579 acc=0.800 route_ce=1.0608 div=0.0625 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 1200: loss=2.3685 acc=0.800 route_ce=1.0533 div=0.0625 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 1400: loss=1.8741 acc=0.900 route_ce=1.0558 div=0.0625 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 1600: loss=2.6636 acc=0.750 route_ce=1.0510 div=0.0625 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 1800: loss=2.0355 acc=0.850 route_ce=1.0589 div=0.0625 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n ep 1999: loss=2.0049 acc=0.850 route_ce=1.0568 div=0.0625 wr=0.11 rd=0.11 skip=0.79 occ=17.3\n Phase 1 done in 817s\n\nPhase 2: Imitation learning (5000 ep)\n ep 0: loss=4.9642 acc=0.000 route_ce=1.0658 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 500: loss=4.9419 acc=0.050 route_ce=1.0539 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 1000: loss=4.9842 acc=0.050 route_ce=1.0599 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 1500: loss=5.0044 acc=0.050 route_ce=1.0559 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71"}],"timestamp":1774330915608}}
{"type":"message","id":"deb18a04","parentId":"c74090a2","timestamp":"2026-03-24T05:42:44.764Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see both phases clearly. Let me analyze:\n\n**Phase 1 (Supervised pre-training, 2000 ep):**\n- `skip=0.79` throughout — 79% of tokens skip ALL expert computation\n- `route_ce` drops from 1.1545 to 1.0568 — router improves slightly but not much\n- `div=0.0561` → 0.0625 — near zero expert diversity\n- `wr=0.11`, `rd=0.11` throughout — both constant, weight=0.11 for both route_ce and... \"rd\" probably regularization/derivative?\n- `occ=17.3` — occupancy around 17.3, which seems to mean only 17.3% of expert capacity used (or some occupancy metric)\n\n\n- Loss plummets from 5.75 to 2.0 while accuracy fluctuates between 0.75-0.90 but the model never actually learns to route — it just figures out how to pass through without engaging experts\n\n**Phase 2 (Imitation learning, 5000 ep):**\n- `skip=0.71` — actually improved slightly from 0.79, meaning more tokens are now engaging with experts\n- `blkd=0.71` — blocking mechanism kicks in at 0.71, which correlates with the skip rate, suggesting tokens are being deliberately blocked from routing\n- `wr=0.29`, `rd=0.00` — weight for route_ce increased to 0.29 while regularization/derivative drops to zero\n- `route_ce` barely budges (1.0658 → 1.0559), so the router still isn't learning meaningfully\n- `acc=0.050` throughout — tragic accuracy, though phase 2 seems to be doing something different with a `margin` metric I need to understand\n\nThe blocking behavior is actually the most telling signal here — `blkd=0.71` means 71% of tokens are being blocked from routing, which tracks with the skip rate. But here's what's interesting: `skip=0.71` in phase 2 while `blkd=0.71` in phase 2, yet in phase 1 `skip=0.79` with no blocking metric at all. This suggests the blocking mechanism was either added between phases or the two phases are measuring skip differently — phase 1 might be counting blocked tokens as skipped, while phase 2 distinguishes between the two.\n\nThe core problem is becoming clearer: the router is almost entirely inactive (`skip` or `blkd` > 0.70 everywhere), the accuracy remains catastrophically low, and the `route_ce` barely budges across 7000 total epochs. The model isn't learning to route at all — it's either defaulting to a pass-through or the blocking mechanism is preventing routing from ever really happening.\n\nI need to understand what those blocking tokens are doing. If 71% are being blocked, what are the other 29% actually computing? The `blkd=0.71` metric could mean blocked token proportion, or it could be the blocked loss term itself. Let me figure out which before diagnosing further. Either way, the SR-MoE isn't functioning as intended — the routing is mostly broken. My instinct is that there's likely a single dominant expert being selected almost every time, which would explain why the model converges to \"mostly skip\" as a learned behavior. The `margin=0.0000` throughout phase 2 is suspicious too — either the margin loss isn't being computed at all, or it's stuck at zero because the top-k selection never triggers. If I knew what wr and rd represented, I could figure out whether the routing coefficients are actually being optimized or just frozen.\n\nLooking at the architecture: if this is supposed to be a sparse router selecting top-k experts from a much larger pool, then having 17.3% occupancy on just 17 experts would mean each expert fires way too often for a truly sparse system. That suggests either the sparsity constraint isn't enforcing actual expert exclusion, or the router is selecting many of the same experts repeatedly and the model never learns to distribute load.\n\nThe real problem is the 0.79 skip rate throughout training. I think what's happening is the SR in SR-MoE stands for some kind of regularization that creates an identity path or skip connection that's too attractive—the router learns that routing around the experts entirely is cheaper than selecting them, so it just defaults to skipping. That's why even during imitation learning when we want the model to mimic specific behaviors, it's still mostly bypassing the expert computation. The fix would involve either removing that skip option entirely or penalizing it enough that routing through experts becomes the better choice.","thinkingSignature":"00ff2f51fda1cbc4ba3dbb6ec76fba63399a71ff92d66bb1c5191969a7ee3f00"},{"type":"text","text":"This is way more revealing now. A few things stand out:\n\n**The `blkd` metric in Phase 2 is new and crucial.** `blkd=0.71` = 71% of tokens are being *blocked* from routing. That means only ~29% even TRY to route. Of that 29%, the `route_ce` barely moves. So your router is essentially inactive on ~70%+ of tokens by design (blocked), and doesn't learn on the rest.\n\n**Phase 1 `skip=0.79` is structural, not learned.** It didn't change across 2000 epochs — that's not the model \"learning to skip,\" that's the skip path being the default that never gets overridden because the routing loss is too weak (`wr=0.11`).\n\n**Phase 2 `acc=0.050` is catastrophic.** After 1500 imitation learning epochs, accuracy is 5%. That's basically random. The model isn't learning the task at all.\n\n**The core issue:** The blocking mechanism (`blkd`) + the weak routing loss means the model can't learn to route. And the `margin=0.0000` suggests whatever margin-based regularizer you have isn't firing either.\n\n**My questions:**\n1. What is `blkd` actually measuring? Is it a hard block (router says \"blocked\") or is it that the expert selection returns fewer than K experts?\n2. What is `wr` and `rd`? (route weight and regularization derivative?)\n3. What's the architecture — how many experts, what is K in top-K?\n4. Is there a \"skip connection\" or identity bypass in the MoE layer that lets tokens go through without any expert computation?\n\nBecause if `skip=0.79` is the identity bypass being taken 79% of the time, that's a design problem — you need to either remove the bypass or make the routing path strictly better than the bypass."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":1377,"cacheRead":13992,"cacheWrite":112385,"totalTokens":127797,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774330915615}}
