route_ce=0.8050 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 2000: loss=4.7094 acc=0.000 route_ce=0.8147 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 2500: loss=4.7630 acc=0.000 route_ce=0.8095 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 3000: loss=4.7061 acc=0.000 route_ce=0.8042 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 3500: loss=4.7383 acc=0.100 route_ce=0.8089 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71\n ep 4000: loss=4.7471 acc=0.050 route_ce=0.8123 margin=0.0000 wr=0.29 rd=0.00 skip=0.71 blkd=0.71"}],"timestamp":1774336864796}}
{"type":"message","id":"f28adc55","parentId":"e25885ca","timestamp":"2026-03-24T07:22:34.152Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Phase 1 results are interesting:\n- `route_ce` dropped from 1.1764 to 0.8127 — the oracle routing is being learned (the router is predicting oracle actions correctly)\n- But `wr=0.11`, `rd=0.11`, `skip=0.79` — same as before! So oracle routing is being learned but the actual behavior didn't change\n- `acc=0.850` — good accuracy on the task\n\nThe Phase 2 results are the same as before:\n- `acc=0.000-0.050` — basically random\n- `rd=0.00` — zero reads\n\n\n- `wr=0.29` — writes happening\n- `skip=0.71` — 71% skip\n- `blkd=0.71` — 71% blocked\n- `route_ce` barely budged from Phase 1\n\nSo my fixes #1, #2, and #5 didn't work. The route CE still isn't capturing what matters. I'm realizing Fix #3 shouldn't even be active yet since we're only 5000 epochs into Phase 2 and the transition happens at epoch 300. But even so, the fact that `acc` is stuck at zero tells me the model isn't learning the right behavior.\n\nThe real problem is that removing the `detach()` didn't help. Even though the router gets the full hidden state now, the write fraction stayed at 0.11 during Phase 1 when the oracle controls routing, so the writes aren't being driven by what the router is learning. The issue runs deeper — the router isn't learning to route to WRITEs effectively in the first place. So the router learns to predict oracle SKIPs accurately during Phase 1, but when Phase 2 kicks in at ep 300, it's stuck predicting SKIP for 71% of tokens — which is exactly what the oracle was doing. That means the learned routing never actually improves upon the oracle's behavior, which is the whole point of this approach.\n\nThe core problem is that Phase 1 only teaches the router to imitate oracle routing decisions, but doesn't give it any signal about whether those decisions were actually optimal for task performance. The router learns the pattern without understanding the consequence. So in Phase 2 when it has to make independent decisions, it just falls back to what it was trained to do. So when Phase 2 kicks in, the model falls back to mostly skipping because it never learned to actually use memory for the task—it just memorized the oracle's skip-heavy pattern. The task itself might not actually require memory at all, which would explain why the oracle got away with skipping so much. I need to figure out whether the query steps are even retrieving useful information from the encoded state, or if the whole architecture is just gaming the loss without solving the real problem. The hard part is that Phase 1's oracle routing doesn't learn what actually matters—using memory effectively. So Phase 2 starts from a weak baseline and the model just keeps skipping instead of adapting.\n\nI'm realizing the route CE loss from Phase 1 might be counterproductive: the oracle's 79% skip rate gets baked in as the default, so when Phase 2 tries to learn READ actions, it's fighting against a router that was trained to predict skips. The masking helps with Fix #5, but I need to think through whether the Phase 2 behavior actually improves from here.\n\nThe real problem is that `acc=0` tells me the model isn't retrieving useful information during queries—either there's nothing in memory to retrieve, or the retrieval mechanism itself is broken. With `blkd=0.71`, the budget enforcer is blocking most READ attempts, which means even if the router wants to read, it's being forced back to skip. So the model is trapped: it can't read because the budget blocks it, and it can't build useful memory because it never learned to write effectively in the first place.\n\nThe route CE loss stays low because it's just predicting skip—the masking prevents it from learning anything useful. I need to check what's actually being logged in the metrics and whether the architecture is even capable of doing what we're asking it to do.\n\nLooking at the Phase 2 loop structure, when `use_oracle=True` it calls the oracle schedule, but once we hit the transition step and set `use_oracle=False`, the model should be running with learned routing. The question is whether the model ever actually gets a chance to learn meaningful routing decisions during this phase, or if it's just running the oracle the entire time.\n\nThe logs show `ep 500` has `blkd=0.71`, which suggests oracle routing is still in effect since it matches Phase 1's behavior. But if the 300-step transition already passed by ep 300, why isn't `use_oracle` being set to False earlier? I need to look more carefully at how the transition logic actually works in the code. I see—the script that was supposed to add the gradual transition to Phase 2 wasn't actually applied to the training loop, so it still has the hard switch from oracle to learned routing at episode 300. But the logs show `blkd=0.71` even at episode 500, which shouldn't happen if the switch already occurred, so something else might be going on here.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully, `rd=0.00` in Phase 2 suggests the model is stuck predicting SKIP for every step, while `blkd=0.71` means the BudgetEnforcer is blocking most actions. This could mean either the learned routing is defaulting to SKIP while the enforcer simultaneously blocks most non-SKIP actions, or the model just isn't routing at all. Let me trace through what Fix #3 was actually supposed to do and whether it was applied correctly.\n\nFix #5 removed the route CE loss contribution for encode-phase SKIPs, which were actually informative signals during training. By masking those out, the model lost its ability to learn that SKIP is correct during encoding—which means it might now be trying to READ during encode steps instead, filling memory with noise and causing the budget enforcer to block everything at query time. The accuracy collapse to zero confirms the model is completely lost. The issue is that SKIP labels during the encode phase are just padding to maintain sequence length, not actual routing decisions the model should learn from. But my Fix #5 was actually removing the signal that teaches the model to SKIP during encoding, which is exactly what it needs to learn. So Fix #5 made things worse by stripping out meaningful SKIP labels that tell the model when to defer action.\n\nI need to revert Fix #5 entirely. But there's a deeper problem: if I don't mask encode-phase SKIPs, the router learns to predict them too well and then defaults to SKIP for everything. The real solution is to make the router only learn from query-phase routing decisions, not encode-phase ones. Or better yet, redesign Phase 1 so the oracle doesn't generate these artificial SKIP labels in the first place.\n\nLooking at the actual logs though, Phase 1 with Fix #1 already shows real improvements—the route_ce dropped significantly and accuracy is solid at 0.850. The problem is Phase 2, where the model has to make routing decisions without the oracle's guidance, and it's completely failing at that transition. The density loss did add some gradient signal during Phase 1, but Phase 2 is a different beast entirely.\n\nLet me trace through what should happen: after 300 steps, oracle routing kicks in and the model should start learning to READ during query phases. But it's not—the accuracy is stuck near zero and route_ce barely budged. The density loss might be keeping it artificially low by just predicting the encode-phase SKIPs, but that's not actually helping the model learn what to do when it needs to retrieve information.\n\nThe real problem is likely in the architecture itself. The `write_threshold=0.5` might be too strict for what the oracle actually writes, or the ExternalMemory retrieval might be broken so even when it does READ, it's getting garbage. And I'm realizing Fix #5 actually made things worse by masking out oracle WRITE signals during encoding, which prevented the model from learning when to write in the first place—I need to revert that fix since the oracle's encode-phase WRITEs are actually informative patterns, not noise. The Fix #5 approach is fundamentally flawed because the routing CE loss gets overwhelmed by 79% SKIP labels during Phase 1, drowning out the meaningful READ/WRITE signals that only appear 21% of the time. The real issue is that Phase 2's hard switch from oracle to learned routing at ep 300 leaves the model unable to generalize—it memorized oracle patterns but never learned to apply them to novel situations. I need a different strategy altogether, either redesigning how the model learns across phases or abandoning the routing CE loss in favor of reinforcement learning or behavioral cloning that focuses on query-phase performance.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully, Phase 1 actually showed improvement with Fix #1—the route CE dropped from 1.1764 to 0.8127 and accuracy hit 0.850. But Phase 2's accuracy collapsed to zero, which suggests the problem isn't the Phase 1 changes themselves but rather how the model transitions between phases or how the Phase 2 training signal is configured. The hard switch to `use_oracle=False` at ep 300 might be too abrupt, causing the model to abandon what it learned rather than build on it.\n\nThe model is also being blocked 71% of the time during Phase 2, which means the budget enforcer is preventing reads almost entirely. With memory essentially empty, the query phase can't retrieve useful information, so accuracy stays near zero. The model's routing behavior is also misaligned with the budget—it's trying to read when the budget doesn't allow it, rather than learning to work within the budget constraints.\n\nI need to reconsider the density loss fix since it's likely causing the model to output more non-SKIP actions during Phase 1 encode steps when the oracle would actually skip. Let me trace through the density loss calculation to see how it's affecting the routing decisions.\n\nThe density loss kicks in when the non-SKIP fraction drops below 15%, which is definitely happening with oracle routing, so it's adding a penalty that encourages non-SKIP outputs. But during Phase 1 encode steps with oracle routing, this creates a conflict—the oracle says SKIP, but the model is being pushed toward non-SKIP actions by the density loss.\n\nThe real issue is that Phase 2 still isn't working even with these fixes. I should focus on diagnosing what's actually broken there rather than tweaking Phase 1 parameters. I think the core problem is that Fix #5 is stripping away meaningful oracle signal during encoding phases, leaving the model unable to learn what to actually predict. The route CE loss was working fine in Phase 1 and it's still performing well there, so removing Fix #5 entirely and sticking with the other changes should give us a clearer picture of whether the approach is sound.","thinkingSignature":"2f41f00b05394f4f9b62a4a8b83cc50adc27d22b9f196cae1d1dd2ae2197ff7d"},{"type":"text","text":"The route_ce improvement in Phase 1 (1.18 → 0.81) shows the detach removal worked. But Phase 2 is still broken. Let me analyze what went wrong with the fixes.\n\nFix #5 is actually backwards — masking out encode-phase SKIP labels removes the signal that teaches the router WHEN to skip, and the model instead learns to emit non-SKIP during encode (filling memory with noise). Then at query time, the budget blocks 71% of reads, memory is useless, and accuracy collapses.\n\nFix #5 needs to be reverted:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cqocqgxisefq_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\spark\\fix_revert5.py","content":"import json\n\nwith open(r'C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    nb = json.load(f)\n\nfor cell in nb['cells']:\n    if cell['id'] == '7b05f1f6':\n        src = ''.join(cell['source'])\n\n        # Revert Fix #5 — restore original route CE without masking\n        # The encode-phase SKIP labels ARE informative (teach router WHEN to skip)\n        old_fix5 = '''        # FIX #5: mask out encode-phase SKIP labels from route CE\n        # Oracle SKIP during encode is a crutch, not a real routing decision\n        r_lbl = torch.tensor(oracle_labels, dtype=torch.long, device=DEVICE)\n        route_mask = torch.ones_like(r_lbl, dtype=torch.bool)  # default: include\n        for ti, oa in enumerate(oracle_labels):\n            if oa == IGNORE_INDEX:\n                route_mask[ti] = False\n            elif oa == 0 and ti < QUERY_START:  # SKIP during encode -- skip this label\n                route_mask[ti] = False\n        if route_mask.sum() > 0:\n            masked_r_t = r_t[route_mask]\n            masked_r_lbl = r_lbl[route_mask]\n            r_wt = torch.tensor(self.route_class_weights, dtype=torch.float, device=DEVICE)\n            L_route = F.cross_entropy(masked_r_t, masked_r_lbl, weight=r_wt)\n        else:\n            L_route = torch.tensor(0.0, device=DEVICE)'''\n\n        new_route_ce = '''        r_lbl = torch.tensor(oracle_labels, dtype=torch.long, device=DEVICE)\n        r_wt = torch.tensor(self.route_class_weights, dtype=torch.float, device=DEVICE)\n        L_route = F.cross_entropy(r_t, r_lbl, weight=r_wt, ignore_index=IGNORE_INDEX)'''\n\n        if old_fix5 in src:\n            src = src.replace(old_fix5, new_route_ce)\n            cell['source'] = src.splitlines(keepends=True)\n            print(\"[OK] Reverted Fix #5 — restored original route CE\")\n        else:\n            print(\"[WARN] Fix #5 pattern not found\")\n        break\n\nwith open(r'C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb', 'w', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    json.dump(nb, f)\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":2952,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":112712,"totalTokens":119953,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774336864809}}
