cc={stats[\"accuracy\"]:.3f}  '\r\nLine 9:               f'route_ce={stats[\"route_loss\"]:.4f}  div={stats[\"div_loss\"]:.4f}  '\r\nLine 10:               f'wr={stats[\"write_frac\"]:.2f}  rd={stats[\"read_frac\"]:.2f}  '\r\nLine 11:               f'skip={stats[\"skip_frac\"]:.2f}  occ={stats[\"avg_occupancy\"]:.1f}')\r\nLine 12: print(f'  Phase 1 done in {time.time()-t0:.0f}s\\n')\r\nLine 13: \r\nLine 14: print(f'Phase 2: Imitation learning ({IMITATION_EP} ep)')\r\nLine 15: t0 = time.time()\r\nLine 16: for ep in range(IMITATION_EP):\r\nLine 17:     stats = trainer.train_episode(generate_episode(DEEPSEED + ep + 10000), use_oracle_routing=False)\r\nLine 18:     if ep % 500 == 0 or ep == IMITATION_EP - 1:\r\nLine 19:         print(f'  ep {ep:5d}: loss={stats[\"loss\"]:.4f}  acc={stats[\"accuracy\"]:.3f}  '","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774337053673}}
{"type":"message","id":"d9780e8b","parentId":"0df93593","timestamp":"2026-03-24T07:25:17.133Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! The Phase 2 loop is:\n```python\nfor ep in range(IMITATION_EP):\n    stats = trainer.train_episode(generate_episode(DEEPSEED + ep + 10000), use_oracle_routing=False)\n```\n\nThis uses `use_oracle_routing=False` from the start! My Fix #3 script failed because the string didn't match exactly. And the Phase 2 hard switch is still there.\n\nNow I understand the full picture of what happened:\n\n1. Phase 1 with oracle routing (`use_oracle_routing=True`) → `acc=0.850`, `route_ce=0.81` — decent\n\n\n2. Phase 2 immediately flips to learned routing (`use_oracle_routing=False`) from episode 0, which is way too abrupt. The model has never encountered this condition before, so it's completely unprepared and accuracy plummets to near zero.\n3. The model tries to route but gets blocked by the BudgetEnforcer about 71% of the time, and it never learns to emit READ actions to access memory.\n4. Fix #3 wasn't actually applied to Phase 2, so the transition is still a hard switch instead of the gradual shift I intended.\n5. The fundamental issue is that the model needs practice with learned routing during Phase 1 so it's ready when Phase 2 kicks in.\n6. My density loss encourages non-SKIP emissions during Phase 1's encode steps, but that doesn't help Phase 2 where the model needs to learn routing from scratch.\n7. The real solution is to gradually introduce learned routing in Phase 2 so the model can adapt progressively rather than being thrown into the deep end.\n\nFor the immediate next step, I should focus on Phase 2 and implement the transition properly—starting with a warm-up period where the oracle guides the routing, then slowly letting the model take over.\n\nThe hard switch to `use_oracle_routing=False` at episode 0 is catastrophic because the model immediately faces query steps it's never practiced on. What if I introduced learned routing much earlier during Phase 1's encode steps? The encode phases are mostly SKIPs anyway, so the model could practice on those before tackling queries. Or maybe the real problem is that Phase 1 encode steps don't have informative signals to learn from, so I need to rethink what the model actually practices during that phase.\n\nDuring Phase 1, the model should be learning what the RIGHT oracle routing looks like, but Fix #5 stripped out encode SKIPs so the model doesn't know when to skip. Without Fix #5, the route CE loss would teach the model that oracle routing is mostly SKIP during encode and sometimes WRITE during query, which is actually what the model needs to learn.\n\nIn Phase 2, the model would then know to mostly SKIP during encode and WRITE during query, but that's still not using READ during queries, which is the actual bottleneck for accuracy. The real question is whether learning from the oracle's WRITE-only pattern in Phase 2 would actually help the model figure out when to READ at query time.\n\nThe model's accuracy at ep 2000 was 0.850 with oracle routing, so the memory was being used correctly then—but that was just imitating the oracle, not learning the underlying strategy. When the model switches to learned routing in Phase 2 and mostly emits WRITE at query steps, it's overwriting memory with query embeddings instead of reading from it, which destroys the very information it needs. The architecture fundamentally can't learn to READ during queries because READ would retrieve garbage rather than useful key-value pairs.\n\nLooking at the query step logic more carefully, if the router selects WRITE, the model writes the query's embedding to memory—which is useless since there's no key to retrieve it later. The memory mechanism relies on write operations having meaningful keys, so when a query writes its own embedding, it clobbers the actual useful data. I should probably revert Fix #5 and instead focus on the Phase 2 transition, where the real problem might be that the model struggles to learn READ actions at all.\n\nThe density loss might actually be pushing the model toward non-SKIP actions during Phase 1 query steps when it should be more selective. I'm torn between a few directions: either accept that Phase 1 won't improve much and focus entirely on Phase 2, or try mixing in some learned routing during Phase 1 encode steps so the model gets more practice with non-SKIP decisions before Phase 2 kicks in. Or I could just remove the density loss and Fix #5 entirely and go back to the basics. But reverting Fix #5 might just undo any progress I've made—the Phase 1 route_ce actually got worse in the second run, which is puzzling.\n\nLooking at the numbers more carefully, Phase 1 with the density loss showed worse route_ce compared to the original run, which suggests the density loss is actually hurting the routing signal, not helping it. So the most practical thing to do is revert Fix #5 since it made things worse, keep the other fixes that seem to help, and make sure Phase 2 transitions properly. Though I'm second-guessing myself on whether removing Fix #5 will actually make Phase 2 worse by eliminating encode SKIP signal...\n\nActually, looking at the architecture more carefully: during encode steps, the model sees the current value and emits an action, then during query steps it sees a related key and should emit a different action. The encode-phase actions are critical for building useful memory, so masking them out during training means the model won't learn that pattern. That's clearly wrong. I should revert Fix #5 and focus on getting the Phase 2 transition right.","thinkingSignature":"9838753c749f15a9c6cdb19d393d3581e3eb1ccbfe525871143676f800dc708f"},{"type":"text","text":"Found it — Fix #3 never got applied to the Phase 2 loop. It still hard-switches to `use_oracle_routing=False` at episode 0. Also, Fix #5 is backwards — masking encode-phase SKIP labels removes the signal that teaches the router WHEN to skip, which makes the model over-emit non-SKIP (WRITE) during encode phases, filling memory with noise. Then at query time there's nothing useful to read.\n\nTwo fixes to apply now:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u9t26pehn4ly_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\spark\\fix_final.py","content":"import json\n\nwith open(r'C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    nb = json.load(f)\n\nfor cell in nb['cells']:\n    # Fix 1: Revert Fix #5 in trainer (cell 7b05f1f6)\n    if cell['id'] == '7b05f1f6':\n        src = ''.join(cell['source'])\n        old = '''        # FIX #5: mask out encode-phase SKIP labels from route CE\n        # Oracle SKIP during encode is a crutch, not a real routing decision\n        r_lbl = torch.tensor(oracle_labels, dtype=torch.long, device=DEVICE)\n        route_mask = torch.ones_like(r_lbl, dtype=torch.bool)  # default: include\n        for ti, oa in enumerate(oracle_labels):\n            if oa == IGNORE_INDEX:\n                route_mask[ti] = False\n            elif oa == 0 and ti < QUERY_START:  # SKIP during encode -- skip this label\n                route_mask[ti] = False\n        if route_mask.sum() > 0:\n            masked_r_t = r_t[route_mask]\n            masked_r_lbl = r_lbl[route_mask]\n            r_wt = torch.tensor(self.route_class_weights, dtype=torch.float, device=DEVICE)\n            L_route = F.cross_entropy(masked_r_t, masked_r_lbl, weight=r_wt)\n        else:\n            L_route = torch.tensor(0.0, device=DEVICE)'''\n        new = '''        r_lbl = torch.tensor(oracle_labels, dtype=torch.long, device=DEVICE)\n        r_wt = torch.tensor(self.route_class_weights, dtype=torch.float, device=DEVICE)\n        L_route = F.cross_entropy(r_t, r_lbl, weight=r_wt, ignore_index=IGNORE_INDEX)'''\n        if old in src:\n            src = src.replace(old, new)\n            cell['source'] = src.splitlines(keepends=True)\n            print(\"[OK] Reverted Fix #5 in trainer\")\n        else:\n            print(\"[WARN] Fix #5 pattern not found in trainer\")\n        break\n\nfor cell in nb['cells']:\n    # Fix 2: Apply Fix #3 to Phase 2 loop (cell 7c9a68c7)\n    if cell['id'] == '7c9a68c7':\n        src = ''.join(cell['source'])\n        old = 'for ep in range(IMITATION_EP):\\n    stats = trainer.train_episode(generate_episode(DEEPSEED + ep + 10000), use_oracle_routing=False)'\n        new = 'IMITATION_TRANSITION = 300  # FIX #3: oracle for first 300, then gradual learned routing\\nfor ep in range(IMITATION_EP):\\n    use_oracle = (ep < IMITATION_TRANSITION)  # FIX #3\\n    stats = trainer.train_episode(generate_episode(DEEPSEED + ep + 10000), use_oracle_routing=use_oracle)'\n        if old in src:\n            src = src.replace(old, new)\n            cell['source'] = src.splitlines(keepends=True)\n            print(\"[OK] Applied Fix #3 to Phase 2 loop\")\n        else:\n            print(\"[WARN] Phase 2 loop pattern not found\")\n            idx = src.find('use_oracle_routing=False')\n            print(f\"use_oracle_routing=False found at: {idx}\")\n        break\n\nwith open(r'C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb', 'w', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n    json.dump(nb, f)\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":106392,"output":2090,"cacheRead":13992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":122474,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774337053738}}
