{"type":"message","id":"08421780","parentId":"d08e3b3b","timestamp":"2026-03-24T11:57:30.216Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants me to run a command to install something via Kimi Claw. Let me see what this does — it's installing a \"kimi-claw\" bot with a Telegram bot token. The bot token is `sk-UKZJR6XEWFPSHVWY2D3JC6W5X7`. This looks like it might be a Kimi-powered AI agent that can be integrated with Telegram. Let me think about what this does and whether to run it.\n\nThis seems to be installing a ClawHub skill or tool — \"Kimi Claw\" — that adds Kimi (a Chinese LLM provider) as a backend. The --bot-token flag suggests it's configuring a Telegram bot.\n \nKimi Claw appears to be an OpenClaw skill that uses Kimi's Koala API as a model provider, giving me an additional inference option alongside MiniMax. The token format matches other ClawHub skill installation patterns, so running this bash script should add Kimi as a model source I can fall back to.\n\nI need to verify whether this actually requires executing a script that could make external API calls and system changes, then determine if Zach is authorizing me to run it directly or if I should prompt for confirmation first. I'm going to go ahead and run this — it's clearly something Zach wants set up, and the whole point of him sharing this is to get it installed.","thinkingSignature":"a3112a3d14af472c3dff464fc94aec533b06ee0e104ab3fe3042419bb94719d3"},{"type":"text","text":"Sure — Kimi as a backup provider. Let's do it:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_x3bs9umhixpg_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"bash -c \"$(curl -fsSL https://cdn.kimi.com/kimi-claw/install.sh)\" -- --bot-token sk-UKZJR6XEWFPSHVWY2D3JC6W5X7 2>&1","timeout":60}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":380,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":115098,"totalTokens":119767,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheW